03927nam a22004215i 9781503626256DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036262567 a10.1515/97815036262562doi  a(DE-B1597)581338  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLIT0060002bisacsh1 aHarshav, Benjamin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aExplorations in Poetics /cBenjamin Harshav. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b1 table, 22 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Fictionality and Fields of Reference: A Theoretical Framework -- t2. Metaphor and Frames of Reference: With Examples from Eliot, Rilke, Mayakovsky, Mandelshtam, Pound, Creeley, Amichai, and the New York Times -- t3. An Outline of Integrational Semantics: An Understander’s Theory of Meaning in Context -- t4. The Structure of Semiotic Objects: A Three-Dimensional Model -- t5. On Presentation and Representation in Fiction -- t6. The Meaning of Sound Patterns in Poetry: An Interaction Theory -- t7. “Literariness” Revisited: A Contemporary Manifesto -- t8. The Structure of Non-Narrative Fiction: The First Episode of War and Peace -- tReferences to Chapters 1-8 -- tFRAMEWORKS -- t9. The Elusive Science of Literature: Remarks on the Fields and Responsibilities of the Study of Literature [Tel-Aviv 1968] -- t10. A Unified Theory of the Literary Text [Berkeley 1972] -- tSources of the Chapters -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of essays, originally published at different times, presents a coherent, systematic, and comprehensive theory of the work of literature and its major aspects. The approach, which may be called "Constructive Poetics," does not assume that a work of literature is a text with fixed structures and meanings, but a text that invites the reader to evoke or project a network of interrelated constructs, complementary or contradictory as they may be. The work of literature is not just a narrative, as studies in narratology assume, but a text that projects a fictional world, or an Internal Field of Reference. Meanings in a text are presented through the evocation of "frames of reference" (scenes, characters, ideas, etc.). Language in literature is double-directed: it relates the Internal Field to External Fields and vice versa. The essays explore the problems of fictionality, presentation and representation, metaphor as interaction between several frames of reference, the theory of "Integrational Semantics" in literary and other texts, the meaning of sound patterns in poetry, and the question of "literariness." This theory and its specific aspects were developed by the author in Israel in the 1960s and 1970s and lay at the foundations of the Tel-Aviv School of Poetics. Revived now, it resonates with the current mood in literary criticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362625640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503626256423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503626256/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles